What is the Structure this Data?

This data consists of 113,937 loans and 81 variables for each loan.

What is the Purpose of digging into this Data?

I will be taking a closer look on the BorrowerAPR (Annual Percentage Rate) regarding the loans.

What are the useful variances to consider when looking into the Borrower APR?

Any information given regarding personal information can be useful. Such information cna be: occupation, the rating in Prosper, the loan status, income of the borrower and etc.

plt.xlabel('Borrower APR');

It seems that the Borrower APR is spread out. However, we can see key peek highlights at 0.1, 0.2 and 0.3 marks. It is also worth mentioning that the biggest peek happens around a 0.35-0.36 mark. Since the marks get extended to 0.5 it means that only a few loan have a higher Borrower APR than 4.2 (lets see how many loans exactly have an APR higher than 0.42)

plt.xticks(rotation=30);

So what can we make out of this graphs? First the obvious: The length of most of the loans are 36 months. The ratings of most of the borrowers are among D to A. Most of borrowers are employed and full-time.

  • Second: The distribution of borrowers APR looks multimodal. Most of the values are at the range of 0.05 and 0.4. There are no unusual points and no need to perform any transformations

  • Third, was anything unusual: Like I mentioned beforehand, the distribtuion of monthly income is highly right screwed. Most stated monthly incomes are less than 30k, but some of them are incredibly high, like greater than 100k. Most of borrowers with greater than 100k monthly income only loan less than 5k.

  • Forth: So, the very large stated monthly income may be made up. Overall, Less than 0.3 percent borrowers have stated monthly income greater than 30k. These can be seemed as outlier for the following analysis, so it is better to remove borrower records with income greater than 30k.

Miltivariate Exploration¶

Since before we worked on comparing variable to variable, in this part I want to compare the 'useful' (in my opinion) variable Prosper Rating and Term to variable Original Loan and Borrower APR.

In [49]:

term.add_legend()
Out[49]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x188998291c8>
In [50]:
rating = sb.FacetGrid(data = loan_data_apr, col = 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', height = 5, aspect = 1, col_wrap = 4, col_order = ['AA','A','B','C','D','E','HR'])
rating.map(sb.regplot,'LoanOriginalAmount', 'BorrowerAPR', x_jitter = 0.3, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.1});
rating.add_legend();

So from the plots above I can say the following: Term has no effect and is not affected by the Loan Amount and Borrower APR because we can see that the plots line does not change depending if it is 12, 36 or 60 month term; Loan Original Amount seems to be improving with a better Prosper Rating, but Borrower APR however get worse with a better Prosper Rating. We can also see that once the rating becomes A or AA, then the relation between APR and Loan Amount turns into a positive correlation.

Because the relationship goes from negative to positive it would be intereting to see on a better graph the difference. Thats why in the next plot I will try to further observe the change in Borrowers APR all depending on the Term and Prosper Rating (Alpha).

In [51]:
plt.figure(figsize = [8,8])

                    palette = 'Greens', linestyles = '', dodge=0.5, ci = 'sd', order = rate_order)
plt.title('Borrower APR across Rating and Term')
plt.ylabel('Mean Borrower APR')

So, from the plot above it is clearly seen that Borrower APR inscrease as well as the borrow Term as the Ratings becomes AA and A. However as the Rating goes down to B up to HR, so does the borrow Term and borrowers APR.

The only variable we have left to see the relation with is the Loan Original Amount. So what will happen with the variable once we put it against the Rating and Term as well.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest? Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features

This exploration (multivariate) has shown the following:

  • Borrowers APR goes down as it climbs on the Prosper Ratings in terms of borrow Terms. However, it suddenly improves from negative relation to positive as the Prosper Rating goes from HR level towards AA. (We can see that sudden change in the transition from Rating B to A)
  • When does the same on Loan Original Amount, then we can see a constant positive relation with Prosper Rating and Term. However, the relation gets better as well (borrow term amounts) when the Prosper Ratings goes up from HR to AA, which was similarly seen with Borrowers APR.
